** The Third Self: Mary Oliver on Time=2C Concentration=2C the Artist=E2=
=80=99s Task=2C and the Central Commitment of the Creative Life (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2016/10/12/mary-oliver-upstream-creativity-power-time=
/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1594206708/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D6c7=
3834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CIn the wholeheartedness of concentration=2C=E2=80=9D the poet Jan=
e Hirshfield wrote in her beautiful inquiry into the effortless effort of=
 creativity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/21/jane-hirshfield-conc=
entration/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cworld and=
 self begin to cohere. With that state comes an enlarging: of what may be=
 known=2C what may be felt=2C what may be done.=E2=80=9D But concentration=
 is indeed a difficult art=2C art=E2=80=99s art=2C and its difficulty lies=
 in the constant conciliation of the dissonance between self and world =E2=
=80=94 a difficulty hardly singular to the particular conditions of our ti=
me. Two hundred years before social media=2C the great French artist Eug=
=C3=A8ne Delacroix lamented the necessary torment of avoiding social distr=
actions in creative work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/17/delacro=
ix-journal-solitude/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ; a century a=
nd a half later=2C Agnes Martin admonished aspiring artists to exercise di=
scernment in the interruptions they allow
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/23/agnes-martin-inspiration/?mc_cid=
=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C or else corrupt the mental=2C emotio=
nal=2C and spiritual privacy where inspiration arises.

But just as self-criticism is the most merciless kind of criticism (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/23/against-self-criticism-adam-phillips-un=
forbidden-pleasures/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and self-comp=
assion the most elusive kind of compassion (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/09/05/school-of-life-self-compassion/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) =2C self-distraction is the most hazardous kind of distraction=2C=
 and the most difficult to protect creative work against.

How to hedge against that hazard is what beloved poet Mary Oliver (b. Sept=
ember 10=2C 1935) explores in a wonderful piece titled =E2=80=9COf Power a=
nd Time=2C=E2=80=9D found in the altogether enchanting Upstream: Selected=
 Essays (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1594206708/braipick-20?mc_=
cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.=
org/title/upstream-selected-essays/oclc/942707489&referer=3Dbrief_results?=
mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ).

Mary Oliver

Oliver writes:

It is a silver morning like any other. I am at my desk. Then the phone rin=
gs=2C or someone raps at the door. I am deep in the machinery of my wits.=
 Reluctantly I rise=2C I answer the phone or I open the door. And the thou=
ght which I had in hand=2C or almost in hand=2C is gone. Creative work nee=
ds solitude. It needs concentration=2C without interruptions. It needs the=
 whole sky to fly in=2C and no eye watching until it comes to that certain=
ty which it aspires to=2C but does not necessarily have at once. Privacy=
=2C then. A place apart =E2=80=94 to pace=2C to chew pencils=2C to scribbl=
e and erase and scribble again.

But just as often=2C if not more often=2C the interruption comes not from=
 another but from the self itself=2C or some other self within the self=2C=
 that whistles and pounds upon the door panels and tosses itself=2C splash=
ing=2C into the pond of meditation. And what does it have to say? That you=
 must phone the dentist=2C that you are out of mustard=2C that your uncle=
 Stanley=E2=80=99s birthday is two weeks hence. You react=2C of course. Th=
en you return to your work=2C only to find that the imps of idea have fled=
 back into the mist.

Oliver terms this the =E2=80=9Cintimate interrupter=E2=80=9D and cautions=
 that it is far more perilous to creative work than any external distracti=
on=2C adding:

The world sheds=2C in the energetic way of an open and communal place=2C i=
ts many greetings=2C as a world should. What quarrel can there be with tha=
t? But that the self can interrupt the self =E2=80=94 and does =E2=80=94 i=
s a darker and more curious matter.

Echoing Borges=E2=80=99s puzzlement over our divided personhood (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2016/09/06/borges-and-i/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Oliver sets out to excavate the building blocks of the s=
elf in order to understand its parallel capacities for focused creative fl=
ow and merciless interruption. She identifies three primary selves that sh=
e inhabits=2C and that inhabit her=2C as they do all of us: the childhood=
 self=2C which we spend our lives trying to weave into the continuity of o=
ur personal identity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/07/rebecca-gol=
dstein-personal-identity/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (=E2=80=
=9CThe child I was=2C=E2=80=9D she writes=2C =E2=80=9Cis with me in the pr=
esent hour. It will be with me in the grave.=E2=80=9D); the social self=2C=
 =E2=80=9Cfettered to a thousand notions of obligation=E2=80=9D; and a thi=
rd self=2C a sort of otherworldly awareness.

The first two selves=2C she argues=2C inhabit the ordinary world and are p=
resent in all people; the third is of a different order and comes most eas=
ily alive in artists =E2=80=94 it is where the wellspring of creative ener=
gy resides. She writes:

Certainly there is within each of us a self that is neither a child=2C nor=
 a servant of the hours. It is a third self=2C occasional in some of us=2C=
 tyrant in others. This self is out of love with the ordinary; it is out o=
f love with time. It has a hunger for eternity.

Art by Maurice Sendak for a special edition of the Brothers Grimm fairy ta=
les (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/20/best-brothers-grimm-illustra=
tions/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Oliver contrasts the existential purpose of the two ordinary selves with t=
hat of the creative self:

Say you have bought a ticket on an airplane and you intend to fly from New=
 York to San Francisco. What do you ask of the pilot when you climb aboard=
 and take your seat next to the little window=2C which you cannot open but=
 through which you see the dizzying heights to which you are lifted from t=
he secure and friendly earth?

Most assuredly you want the pilot to be his regular and ordinary self. You=
 want him to approach and undertake his work with no more than a calm plea=
sure. You want nothing fancy=2C nothing new. You ask him to do=2C routinel=
y=2C what he knows how to do =E2=80=94 fly an airplane. You hope he will n=
ot daydream. You hope he will not drift into some interesting meander of t=
hought. You want this flight to be ordinary=2C not extraordinary. So=2C to=
o=2C with the surgeon=2C and the ambulance driver=2C and the captain of th=
e ship. Let all of them work=2C as ordinarily they do=2C in confident fami=
liarity with whatever the work requires=2C and no more. Their ordinariness=
 is the surety of the world. Their ordinariness makes the world go round.

[=E2=80=A6]

In creative work =E2=80=94 creative work of all kinds =E2=80=94 those who=
 are the world=E2=80=99s working artists are not trying to help the world=
 go around=2C but forward. Which is something altogether different from th=
e ordinary. Such work does not refute the ordinary. It is=2C simply=2C som=
ething else. Its labor requires a different outlook =E2=80=94 a different=
 set of priorities.

Part of this something-elseness=2C Oliver argues=2C is the uncommon integr=
ation of the creative self =E2=80=94 the artist=E2=80=99s work cannot be s=
eparated from the artist=E2=80=99s whole life=2C nor can its wholeness be=
 broken down into the mechanical bits-and-pieces of specific actions and h=
abits. (Elsewhere=2C Oliver has written beautifully about how habit gives=
 shape to but must not control our inner lives (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2015/02/20/mary-oliver-long-life-habit/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) ).

Echoing Keats=E2=80=99s notion of =E2=80=9Cnegative capability=2C=E2=80=9D=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/11/01/john-keats-on-negative-capabili=
ty/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Dani Shapiro=E2=80=99s insiste=
nce that the artist=E2=80=99s task is =E2=80=9Cto embrace uncertainty=2C t=
o be sharpened and honed by it=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2013/11/11/dani-shapiro-still-writing-2/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) and Georgia O=E2=80=99Keeffe=E2=80=99s counsel that as an artist yo=
u ought to be =E2=80=9Ckeeping the unknown always beyond you=2C=E2=80=9D (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/08/georgia-okeeffe-sherwood-anderson=
-letters/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Oliver considers the cen=
tral commitment of the creative life =E2=80=94 that of making uncertainty=
 and the unknown the raw material of art:

Intellectual work sometimes=2C spiritual work certainly=2C artistic work a=
lways =E2=80=94 these are forces that fall within its grasp=2C forces that=
 must travel beyond the realm of the hour and the restraint of the habit.=
 Nor can the actual work be well separated from the entire life. Like the=
 knights of the Middle Ages=2C there is little the creatively inclined per=
son can do but to prepare himself=2C body and spirit=2C for the labor to c=
ome =E2=80=94 for his adventures are all unknown. In truth=2C the work its=
elf is the adventure. And no artist could go about this work=2C or would w=
ant to=2C with less than extraordinary energy and concentration. The extra=
ordinary is what art is about.

In a sentiment that calls to mind Van Gogh=E2=80=99s spirited letter on ri=
sk-taking and how inspired mistakes move us forward (https://www.brainpick=
ings.org/2015/11/02/van-gogh-fear-risk/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) =2C Oliver returns to the question of the conditions that coax the c=
reative self into being:

No one yet has made a list of places where the extraordinary may happen an=
d where it may not. Still=2C there are indications. Among crowds=2C in dra=
wing rooms=2C among easements and comforts and pleasures=2C it is seldom s=
een. It likes the out-of-doors. It likes the concentrating mind. It likes=
 solitude. It is more likely to stick to the risk-taker than the ticket-ta=
ker. It isn=E2=80=99t that it would disparage comforts=2C or the set routi=
nes of the world=2C but that its concern is directed to another place. Its=
 concern is the edge=2C and the making of a form out of the formlessness t=
hat is beyond the edge.

Above all=2C Oliver observes from the =E2=80=9Cfortunate platform=E2=80=9D=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/09/mary-oliver-blue-horses-fourth-=
sign-of-the-zodiac/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of a long=2C p=
urposeful=2C and creatively fertile life=2C the artist=E2=80=99s task is o=
ne of steadfast commitment to the art:

Of this there can be no question =E2=80=94 creative work requires a loyalt=
y as complete as the loyalty of water to the force of gravity. A person tr=
udging through the wilderness of creation who does not know this =E2=80=94=
 who does not swallow this =E2=80=94 is lost. He who does not crave that r=
oofless place eternity should stay at home. Such a person is perfectly wor=
thy=2C and useful=2C and even beautiful=2C but is not an artist. Such a pe=
rson had better live with timely ambitions and finished work formed for th=
e sparkle of the moment only. Such a person had better go off and fly an a=
irplane.

She returns to the problem of concentration=2C which for the artist is a f=
orm=2C perhaps the ultimate form=2C of consecration:

The working=2C concentrating artist is an adult who refuses interruption f=
rom himself=2C who remains absorbed and energized in and by the work =E2=
=80=94 who is thus responsible to the work=E2=80=A6 Serious interruptions=
 to work=2C therefore=2C are never the inopportune=2C cheerful=2C even lov=
ing interruptions which come to us from another.

[=E2=80=A6]

It is six A.M.=2C and I am working. I am absentminded=2C reckless=2C heedl=
ess of social obligations=2C etc. It is as it must be. The tire goes flat=
=2C the tooth falls out=2C there will be a hundred meals without mustard.=
 The poem gets written. I have wrestled with the angel and I am stained wi=
th light and I have no shame. Neither do I have guilt. My responsibility i=
s not to the ordinary=2C or the timely. It does not include mustard=2C or=
 teeth. It does not extend to the lost button=2C or the beans in the pot.=
 My loyalty is to the inner vision=2C whenever and howsoever it may arrive=
=2E If I have a meeting with you at three o=E2=80=99clock=2C rejoice if I am=
 late. Rejoice even more if I do not arrive at all.

There is no other way work of artistic worth can be done. And the occasion=
al success=2C to the striver=2C is worth everything. The most regretful pe=
ople on earth are those who felt the call to creative work=2C who felt the=
ir own creative power restive and uprising=2C and gave to it neither power=
 nor time.

Upstream (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1594206708/braipick-20?mc=
_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a tremendously vitalizing read in=
 its totality=2C grounding and elevating at the same time. Complement it w=
ith Oliver on love and its necessary wildness (https://www.brainpickings.o=
rg/2015/10/20/mary-oliver-felicity-love/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) =2C what attention really means (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015=
/01/20/mary-oliver-molly-malone-cook-our-world/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and the measure of a life well lived (https://www.brainp=
ickings.org/2015/02/09/mary-oliver-blue-horses-fourth-sign-of-the-zodiac/?=
mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Jane Hirshfield o=
n the difficult art of concentration (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/0=
7/21/jane-hirshfield-concentration/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) .


