In an entry from October 23=2C 1855 =E2=80=94 four years before Darwin for=
ever changed our understanding of the interconnectedness of the natural wo=
rld =E2=80=94 Thoreau writes beautifully about our kinship with trees:

Now is the time for chestnuts. A stone cast against the trees shakes them=
 down in showers upon one=E2=80=99s head and shoulders. But I cannot excus=
e myself for using the stone. It is not innocent=2C it is not just=2C so t=
o maltreat the tree that feeds us. I am not disturbed by considering that=
 if I thus shorten its life I shall not enjoy its fruit so long=2C but am=
 prompted to a more innocent course by motives purely of humanity. I sympa=
thize with the tree=2C yet I heaved a big stone against the trunks like a=
 robber=2C =E2=80=94 not too good to commit murder. I trust that I shall n=
ever do it again. These gifts should be accepted=2C not merely with gentle=
ness=2C but with a certain humble gratitude. The tree whose fruit we would=
 obtain should not be too rudely shaken even. It is not a time of distress=
=2C when a little haste and violence even might be pardoned. It is worse t=
han boorish=2C it is criminal=2C to inflict an unnecessary injury on the t=
ree that feeds or shadows us. Old trees are our parents=2C and our
parents=E2=80=99 parents=2C perchance. If you would learn the secrets of N=
ature=2C you must practice more humanity than others. The thought that I w=
as robbing myself by injuring the tree did not occur to me=2C but I was af=
fected as if I had cast a rock at a sentient being=2C =E2=80=94 with a dul=
ler sense than my own=2C it is true=2C but yet a distant relation. Behold=
 a man cutting down a tree to come at the fruit! What is the moral of such=
 an act?

This is the question Marianne Moore asked=2C and so gloriously answered=2C=
 when she saved a tree with a poem (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/=
13/marianne-moore-camperdown-elm/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 in this selfsame park. I think now of James Baldwin and his lamentation t=
hat =E2=80=9Csomething awful is happening to a civilization=2C when it cea=
ses to produce poets.=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/13/j=
ames-baldwin-the-artists-struggle-for-integrity/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_ei=
d=3D[UNIQID])


