** Why Anonymity Is More Artistically Rewarding Than Fame: Virginia Woolf=
 on Elena Ferrante (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/10/11/virginia-wool=
f-orlando-fame-elena-ferrante/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/015670160X/braipick-20When?mc_cid=
=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID] Virginia Woolf published Orlando: A Biogr=
aphy (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/015670160X/braipick-20?mc_cid=
=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/orlando-a-biography/oclc/297407&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D6c=
73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) on October 11=2C 1928=2C she revolutionized=
 the politics of LGBT love (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/11/virgi=
nia-woolf-orlando-lesbian-readings/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) with this groundbreaking novel inspired by and dedicated to her longtime=
 lover (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/28/virginia-woolf-vita-sackv=
ille-west/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and lifelong friend (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2013/03/28/afterwords-virginia-woolf-condolenc=
e-letters/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Vita Sackville-West.

In a testament to the famous assertion that =E2=80=9Cfiction is the lie th=
at tells the truth=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/03/n=
eil-gaiman-view-from-the-cheap-seats-reading/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) the novel has stood the test of time not only as an immensel=
y pleasurable work of art=2C which Vita=E2=80=99s son aptly described as=
 =E2=80=9Cthe longest and most charming love letter in literature=2C=E2=80=
=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/28/virginia-woolf-vita-sackvill=
e-west/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) but as a ceaseless wellspr=
ing of truth and wisdom on such elemental existential concerns as the elas=
ticity of time (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05/04/virginia-woolf-or=
lando-time/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the nature of memo=
ry (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/26/virginia-woolf-orlando-memory=
/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the fluidity of gender (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/01/virginia-woolf-orlando-clothing-gende=
r/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the enlivening power of ill=
usion (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/25/virginia-woolf-orlando-ill=
usions/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and our propensity for=
 self-doubt in creative
work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/25/virginia-woolf-writing-self=
-doubt/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . It is the rare kind of b=
ook which=2C once read=2C accompanies you as a sage silent companion throu=
ghout life=2C always aglow with the perfect insight to illuminate any situ=
ation or struggle.

Art by Aleksandr Zinoviev=2C 1921 (New York Public Library public domain a=
rchive)

One such perfect insight came to mind in light of the recent parasitic pap=
arazzo=E2=80=99s alleged unmasking of Elena Ferrante (http://www.wbur.org/=
onpoint/2016/10/05/elena-ferrante-real-name?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) . Nearly a century earlier=2C Woolf addressed the question at th=
e heart of this egregious violation of artistic choice and integrity by ju=
xtaposing the rewards of fame with those of anonymity=2C or what she calle=
d =E2=80=9Cobscurity=2C=E2=80=9D in the original sense of the word =E2=80=
=94 the state of being not-known=2C of having one=E2=80=99s identity conce=
aled=2C of being hidden from view in the public eye.

Woolf writes:

While fame impedes and constricts=2C obscurity wraps about a man like a mi=
st; obscurity is dark=2C ample=2C and free; obscurity lets the mind take i=
ts way unimpeded. Over the obscure man is poured the merciful suffusion of=
 darkness. None knows where he goes or comes. He may seek the truth and sp=
eak it; he alone is free; he alone is truthful; he alone is at peace.

Extolling the value of obscurity as =E2=80=9Cthe delight of having no name=
=2C but being like a wave which returns to the deep body of the sea=2C=E2=
=80=9D Woolf adds:

Obscurity rids the mind of the irk of envy and spite; [it] sets running i=
n the veins the free waters of generosity and magnanimity; and allows givi=
ng and taking without thanks offered or praise given.

Woolf=E2=80=99s words offer the perfect affirmation of Ferrante=E2=80=99s=
 artistic choice to use a pseudonym=2C which she herself had articulated t=
o her Italian publisher in a beautiful letter penned on September 21=2C 19=
91=2C shortly before the publication of her debut novel=2C Troubling Love.=
 The letter was later included in the Ferrante anthology Frantumaglia (htt=
p://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1609452925/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D6c7383=
4c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . She writes:

You asked me what I intend to do for the promotion of Troubling Love=E2=80=
=A6 You asked the question ironically=2C with one of your bemused expressi=
ons=E2=80=A6 I do not intend to do anything for Troubling Love=2C anything=
 that might involve the public engagement of me personally. I=E2=80=99ve a=
lready done enough for this long story: I wrote it. If the book is worth a=
nything=2C that should be sufficient. I won=E2=80=99t participate in discu=
ssions and conferences=2C if I=E2=80=99m invited. I won=E2=80=99t go and a=
ccept prizes=2C if any are awarded to me. I will never promote the book=2C=
 especially on television=2C not in Italy or=2C as the case may be=2C abro=
ad. I will be interviewed only in writing=2C but I would prefer to limit e=
ven that to the indispensable minimum. I am absolutely committed in this s=
ense to myself and my family. I hope not to be forced to change my mind.

[=E2=80=A6]

I believe that books=2C once they are written=2C have no need of their aut=
hors. If they have something to say=2C they will sooner or later find read=
ers; if not=2C they won=E2=80=99t. There are plenty of examples. I very mu=
ch love those mysterious volumes=2C both ancient and modern=2C that have n=
o definite author but have had and continue to have an intense life of the=
ir own. They seem to me a sort of nighttime miracle=2C like the gifts of t=
he Befana [a fairy-like character of Italian folklore]=2C which I waited=
 for as a child. I went to bed in great excitement and in the morning I wo=
ke up and the gifts were there=2C but no one had seen the Befana. True mir=
acles are the ones whose makers will never be known; they are the very sma=
ll miracles of the secret spirits of the home or the great miracles that l=
eave us truly astonished. I still have this childish wish for marvels=2C l=
arge or small=2C I still believe in them.

Complement with Einstein on the fickle nature of fame and the true rewards=
 of work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/09/albert-einstein-fame-le=
tter/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Woolf on th=
e relationship between loneliness and creativity (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2016/06/16/virginia-woolf-loneliness/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) =2C what makes love last (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/=
11/virginia-woolf-on-relationships-marriage/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) =2C and the epiphany that taught her what it means to be an art=
ist (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/09/09/virginia-woolf-cotton-wool-m=
oments-of-being/?mc_cid=3D6c73834c6e&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


