s-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">[=E2=80=A6]<=
/p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;c=
olor: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height=
: 170%;text-align: left;">I believe that books=2C once they are written=2C=
 have no need of their authors. If they have something to say=2C they will=
 sooner or later find readers; if not=2C they won=E2=80=99t. There are ple=
nty of examples. I very much love those mysterious volumes=2C both ancient=
 and modern=2C that have no definite author but have had and continue to h=
ave an intense life of their own. They seem to me a sort of nighttime mira=
cle=2C like the gifts of the Befana [a fairy-like character of Italian fo=
lklore]=2C which I waited for as a child. I went to bed in great excitemen=
t and in the morning I woke up and the gifts were there=2C but no one had=
 seen the Befana. True miracles are the ones whose makers will never be kn=
own; they are the very small miracles of the secret spirits of the home or=
 the great miracles that leave us truly astonished. I still have this chil=
dish wish for marvels=2C large or small=2C I still believe in them.</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust:=
